Final considerations:
In general, ARGMAX is more efficient than Matlab builtin function MAX (at least, along one dimension).
There are a lot of reasons for this: the different argument checking method,
ARGMAX is less general and thus easier to be optimized than MAX, etc...
The use of ARGMAXMIN_MEX result to be SIGNIFICANTLY faster than Matlab builtin MAX in both dimensions.
This is due mainly due to the absence of argument checking, but other factors play an important role here.
Working on different dimensions dramatically changes the elapsed times.
This is due to the fact that Matlab stores matrices column-wise into the physical memory.
